You see a group of refugees running
away to another kingdom.

00:03:22.177 --> 00:03:24.786
You see natural disaster, you see 
earthquakes, you see

00:03:25.009 --> 00:03:27.026
the forest being ripped apart.

00:03:29.853 --> 00:03:34.315
And we get to see these young
college students confront that

00:03:34.932 --> 00:03:38.084
with us and for us, as our proxies.

00:03:39.316 --> 00:03:43.251
[SINGING]
"Maybe we forgot"

00:03:43.844 --> 00:03:46.291
ETHAN HEARD: There are two professional 
designers working on the show.

00:03:46.499 --> 00:03:47.907
Reid Thompson designed the set,

00:03:48.116 --> 00:03:50.995
and Mio Guberinic designed costumes,

00:03:51.365 --> 00:03:54.596
and they were able to come to campus
early on in our class

00:03:54.899 --> 00:03:57.475
and share all their design work 
with the students, which I think

00:03:57.668 --> 00:04:01.107
really kicked off our process
in an exciting way.

00:04:01.289 --> 00:04:03.811
We wanted to make a fresh production

00:04:04.084 --> 00:04:07.844
so our design really updates 
some of the clothing.

00:04:08.099 --> 00:04:11.205
Our design avoids trees.

00:04:12.994 --> 00:04:16.707
In the first act, we're in a more 
comfortable, fantastical, colorful place.

00:04:17.522 --> 00:04:20.274
And in Act II, that's really stripped away.

00:04:20.532 --> 00:04:28.548
And we go from a theatrical world to a 
more raw, real, naked scary dark place.

00:04:28.803 --> 00:04:30.116
We play with a lot of shadows

00:04:30.307 --> 00:04:34.452
and so we theatricalize a lot of the 
magical moments in either

00:04:35.139 --> 00:04:37.731
rear shadow play or frontal.

00:04:38.068 --> 00:04:42.147
So we have a combination of roving lights
on the ground and flashlights

00:04:42.339 --> 00:04:45.026
and all different kinds of cutouts.

00:04:45.268 --> 00:04:47.524
We even have a special effect in Act II.

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:54.708
These big bookcases suddenly dump
hundreds of books. They tilt over

00:04:55.091 --> 00:04:57.187
and make a pretty horrifying sound.

00:04:57.413 --> 00:04:59.235
The first time we did that 
with the students

00:04:59.429 --> 00:05:03.571
there was genuine fear
and adrenaline in the room.

00:05:03.892 --> 00:05:10.643
And that was really gratifying to see
how the design was inspiring the actors

00:05:12.403 --> 00:05:16.261
and really turning them on to the story
and the experience.

00:05:17.269 --> 00:05:22.387
I mean, one of the giants in the field 
of Sondheim study is Stacy Wolf,

00:05:22.691 --> 00:05:26.196
who founded the music theater
certificate  here

00:05:26.533 --> 00:05:29.588
and this is really the kickoff 
production of that new program

00:05:29.879 --> 00:05:31.779
so we thought it would be delicious

00:05:32.006 --> 00:05:34.869
if Stacy would take on the role 
of the Giant herself

00:05:35.091 --> 00:05:38.804
We had a fabulous recording session with
Stacy and Hillel, our sound designer

00:05:39.238 --> 00:05:43.540
and she just is chewing the scenery. 
She's a fabulous actor.

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:46.540
